@database 303tracker_menu.guide
@author "Jeroen Schellekens"
@$VER: 1.0
@font topaz.font 8
@wordwrap
@width 80
@index Index1

@node Main "Main"
This guide gives you a description of each menu-item available in
303tracker.
@endnode

@node Clears "Menu item 101"
Clear Song - @{b}No keyboard shortcut available@{ub}
-------------------------------------------
Clears the whole song in memory and reset additional parameters like tempo
and patternlengths and patternnames. So you can start all over again!
@endnode

@node Loadso "Menu item 103"
Load Song - @{b}Right Amiga + O@{ub}
---------------------------
With this item you load a song into memory. If another song is still in
memory, it will be cleared before a new song will be loaded! So all
unsaved data will be gone after loading a song!

You can load the following file formats:
* 303tracker
* 303emu script (scripts in ASCII-text, supported by 303emu V2.x)
* Octamed (popular music program, 303tracker only supports MMD1!)
* Protracker modules

The Octamed and Protracker loaders have some limitations. Only the
note-data of the modules will be loaded. All other data such as samples
and command data will be ignored.
@endnode

@node Saveso "Menu item 104"
Save Song - @{b}Right Amiga + W@{ub}
---------------------------
With this item you save the song you made. If you save it in the
303tracker fileformat (the custom type), it will save all data concerning
the song, like notes, patternlengths, patternnames, tempo and also the the
effect- and render-settings. All other settings like MIDI-settings not
however, because these settings are set and memorized in the configuration.

Note: the metronome-settings (wich sample is assigned to play along with
      the pattern or song) are neither saved with song, neither the sample
      itself!

303tracker saves the following fileformats:
* 303tracker
* 303emu script (scripts in ASCII-text, supported by 303emu V2.x)

The 303emu script saver doesn't save the whole song however, as 303emuV2.x
does only support a limited number of notes. Instead a requester will ask
you wich pattern you want to save.
@endnode

@node Arrang "Menu item 106"
Arrange - @{b}Right Amiga + E@{ub}
-------------------------
This menu item will lead you to the Arrange window, where you can arrange
the patterns to create a whole song. It works somewhat like the Playing
Sequence in Octamed, with some Qbass influences.
@endnode

@node Setnam "Menu item 108"
Set Name - @{b}Right Amiga + N@{ub}
--------------------------
With this item you can set the name of the song. It's not a very special
function, but it keeps, apart from the filename (if you've saved or loaded
a song) an additional name.
@endnode

@node Import "Menu item 110"
Import Exotic - @{b}No keyboard shortcut available@{ub}
----------------------------------------------
Here you can import unusual formats to 303tracker, which tries to interpret
the file format and then loads it into the pattern(s).

At the moment the following file-formats are supported:

-Octamed PrintOut (must be printed as graphic, to a file)
-Iff Ilbm 2 colors pictures (takes the color index 01 as a value and
 converts it to a user-defined parameter)
@endnode

@node Export "Menu item 111"
Export As Module - @{b}No keyboard shortcut available@{ub}
-------------------------------------------------
This function exports ONLY the current pattern as a Protracker module,
which includes the notes, and up to a total of 32 samples (depending on the
length of the pattern) assigned to every note.
@endnode

@node Rando1 "Menu item 113"
Randomize Song - @{b}No keyboard shortcut available@{ub}
-----------------------------------------------
This item will randomize all notes, cutoffs, accent in the song. It's sort
of a chaotic music creator, in this case it makes a whole chaotic song out
of random data.
@endnode

@node Quit01 "Menu item 115"
Quit - @{b}Right Amiga + Q@{ub}
----------------------
Quit the program and get back to Workbench/AmigaDOS. All unsaved data will
be lost!
@endnode

@node Markra "Menu item 201"
Mark Range - @{b}Right Amiga + B@{ub}
----------------------------
@endnode

@node Markal "Menu item 202"
Mark Whole Pattern As Range - @{b}Right Amiga + A@{ub}
---------------------------------------------
Marks the whole current pattern as a range.
@endnode

@node Copyra "Menu item 203"
Copy Range - @{b}Right Amiga + C@{ub}
----------------------------
@endnode

@node Cutran "Menu item 204"
Cut Range - @{b}Right Amiga + X@{ub}
---------------------------
@endnode

@node Paster "Menu item 205"
Paste Range - @{b}Right Amiga + V@{ub}
-----------------------------
@endnode

@node Shift2 "Menu item 207"
Shift/Move Range-data Up or Down - @{b}Right Amiga + J@{ub}
--------------------------------------------------
Just like the horizontal version, it shoves the data. But in this case,
up or down. The value you can alter in the window, means how many steps
up (negative value) or down (positive value) you move the ranged data.
This is of good use, if you want to shift the notes 4 places up, or want
to make variation in the note-length or accents.
Remember, this function has effect (as always) on the selected column.
@endnode

@node Inver1 "Menu item 209"
Invert Ranged-data Horizontally - @{b}Right Amiga + H@{ub}
-------------------------------------------------
This function mirrors all values in the selected column. So all sliders
with a low value (placed to the left) will get a high value (placed right).
@endnode

@node Inver2 "Menu item 210"
Invert Ranged-data Vertically - @{b}Right Amiga + Y@{ub}
-----------------------------------------------
All notes or sliders or data (depends on wich column yu've selected) in the
selected range will be mirrored vertically. This means that the value on
place 00 will get the value of place 31 and vice versa. This is nice for
refreshing results.
@endnode

@node Rando2 "Menu item 212"
Randomize Column - @{b}Right Amiga + Z@{ub}
----------------------------------
Create random notes/values/data in the selected column. If you are out of
inspiration, try this one.
@endnode

@node Transp "Menu item 213"
Transpose Notes - @{b}Right Amiga + T@{ub}
---------------------------------
With this item, you'll get a window where you can change the pitch of all
the notes in the pattern. Notice that this function always and only works
on the note-column. This one is handy for making a certain pattern one
note higher than the previous one, or throw all notes in the pattern one
octave up or down.
@endnode

@node Colopt "Menu item 215"
Column Options - No keyboard shortcut available
-----------------------------------------------
Brings you to a window where you can mark the whole @{b}selected@{ub} column
as a range, or copy, cut, paste and swap a whole column.
@endnode

@node Pop-up "Menu item 217"
Pop-up Edit-Window After Selecting Range?
-----------------------------------------
If you switch this menu-item ON, it will have to following effect:
After selecting a range somewhere in the pattern with your mouse while
holding the @{b}Right@{ub} mousebutton, a window will pop-up, which shows
you some buttons where you can copy, cut or alter the selected range
directly by selecting a function in this window (by pushing the button).
This window will only appear if the Pop-up menu-item is activated.
@endnode

@node Copypa "Menu item 301"
Copy (part of) Pattern - @{b}Alt + F4@{ub}
---------------------------------
Copies a part or the whole current pattern into buffer. Use @{b}Paste Pattern@{ub}
to copy the contents of this buffer into a new pattern. If you just want to
copy the whole pattern, just press @{b}Return@{ub} without changing the values in
the window (wich will appear after selecting this menu-item.)

Note: If you use the keyboard shortcut @{b}Alt + F4@{ub}, you automaticly
      copy the WHOLE pattern without a window popping up!
@endnode

@node Pastep "Menu item 302"
Paste Buffer into Current Pattern - @{b}Alt + F5@{ub}
--------------------------------------------
Copies the contents of the buffer into the current pattern.
@endnode

@node Clearp "Menu item 303"
Cuts (part of) Pattern - @{b}Alt + F3@{ub}
---------------------------------
Cuts (a part of) the current pattern to buffer. A window asks you from
where to where you want to clear it. Press @{b}Return@{ub} to cut the whole
pattern.

Note: By using the keyboard shortcut @{b}Alt + F3@{ub}, you clear the
      WHOLE pattern in one action, so no window will appear.
@endnode

@node Swappa "Menu item 304"
Swap Current Pattern With... - @{b}No keyboard shortcut available@{ub}
-------------------------------------------------------------
With this function you can swap the contents of the current pattern with
another one. A window will appear where you can choose wich pattern you
want to swap the current pattern with. Then, you can choose to swap the
two, and stay at the current pattern, or you can jump to the selected
pattern after the swapping proces.
@endnode

@node Prevpa "Menu item 306"
Goto Previous Pattern - @{b}Alt + CursorLeft@{ub}
----------------------------------------
Jump one pattern back. After this action, the current pattern wich can be
edited is the one BEFORE the old one. This has nothing to do with the place
of the pattern in the arrangement/sequence however! If you want to jump
back one pattern in the arrangement, you have to go to the @{b}Arrange Window@{ub},
found in the @{b}Project Menu@{ub}.
@endnode

@node Nextpa "Menu item 307"
Goto Next Pattern - @{b}Alt + CursorRight@{ub}
-------------------------------------
Jump one pattern forward. After this action, the current pattern wich is
ready for editing is the one AFTER the old one. This has nothing to do with
the place of the pattern in the arrangement however! If you want to jump
forward one pattern in the arrangement, go to the @{b}Arrange Window@{ub},
found in the @{b}Project Menu@{ub}.
@endnode

@node Gotopa "Menu item 308"
Goto Pattern number... - @{b}Alt + G@{ub}
--------------------------------
A window will appear where you can select the pattern wich you want to
edit.
@endnode

@node Plengt "Menu item 310"
Set Pattern Length - @{b}Alt + L@{ub}
----------------------------
Sets the length of the current pattern, until where it has to be played.
All data beyond the given length will be memorized, so if you are not
certain of your action, or you maybe want to enlarge the length later, the
old data will be restored.
In fact, all data further than the length will be editable, so the
pattern-length has only effect on the play- and render-processes.

You can also determine the length by clicking on red 'elastic band' at the
right of the screen. Note that you CAN'T change the start-position of the
pattern, only the the end-position!
@endnode

@node Paname "Menu item 311"
Give the current pattern a name - @{b}Alt + N@{ub}
-----------------------------------------
Every pattern can be given a name, and this function asks you how to name
the current pattern. It's very useful when you are making an arrangement of
all your patterns, but don't know out of your head, wich number is wich
pattern. So you can give your patterns a short description (max. 32 chars).

Note: You have to switch on the information bar by setting @{b}Show Info@{ub}
      on to see the infobar wich prints the name of the current pattern
      being edited.
@endnode

@node Patenv "Menu item 313"
Envelopes of Pattern - @{b}Alt + O@{ub}
------------------------------
Brings you a window where you can display and edit the individual envelopes
of every parameter, just like in the normal pattern-editor, but now you see
the envelopes vertically instead of horizontally displayed.

Also, there's an extra envelope which can be editted, namely the
@{b}Volume Envelope@{ub}!
You can edit each envelope by first selecting its name by clicking on the
cyclebutton top-left. Keep pushing it 'till you the one you want to edit.
@endnode

@node Playpa "Menu item 401"
Play Current Pattern - @{b}Shift + Right Amiga@{ub}
------------------------------------------
Play the current pattern through the Paula Chip, or via the AHI Device.
When the pattern reaches its end, it will start over to play from position
00. It just works like the Protracker and Octamed play-pattern command.
Press @{b}Space@{ub} to stop playing the pattern.

Note: When you've made the right settings with the @{b}Playback@{ub} item
      found in the menu @{b}Settings@{ub}, an external sample or metronome
      can be played along with the pattern. This is very useful to get a
      good impression of the programmed 303loop combined with some rhythm.
@endnode

@node Playso "Menu item 402"
Play Song - @{b}Shift + Alt@{ub}
-----------------------
Play the song, using the arrangement (in other words, the playing sequence)
made with the @{b}Arrangement@{ub} tool, starting from the position wich is
printed in the information-bar.

Note 1: You have to switch on the information bar by setting @{b}Show Info@{ub}
        on. Now the upper menu-bar will be replaced by an information bar
        wich prints the current position in the playing sequence and the
        name of the current pattern being edited.

Note 2: When you've made the right settings with the @{b}Playback@{ub} item
        found in the menu @{b}Settings@{ub}, an external sample or
        metronome can be played along with the song. This is very useful to
        get a good impression of the programmed 303loop combined with some
        rhythm.
@endnode

@node Playmo "Menu item 403"
Here you can select whether you want to suck the dick of a nigger or a
lesbian nazi-hooker.
@endnode

@node Rendgo "Menu item 405"
Render the Song/Pattern to a Sample- @{b}Right Amiga + R@{ub}
----------------------------------------------------
This function is a very important one, because you can render your final
samples with it. After selected this menu-item, you'll get a window where
you can decide whether you want to render a pattern or the whole song, in
wich format (8 or 16 bits precision), if you want to render the effects
(like delay, chorus, distortion) with the sample.

If you press OK, it will start rendering the pattern(s) and when it's
finished, the rendered sample will be displayed in a graphic window.
@endnode

@node Rendqu "Menu item 406"
Render current pattern quickly - @{b}Right Amiga + F@{ub}
------------------------------------------------
Renders the current pattern to a sample, in a special quick way. The
quality of the resulting sample is not optimized and clean as a (final)
rendered sample with the 'Render Go!' item, but it gives a good idea of
what it will sound. Just use it as a preview.

Note: @{b}Render Quick@{ub} does NOT contain: Effects
                                     Equaliser-settings (mixer)
@endnode

@node Savesa "Menu item 408"
Save the Rendered Sample - @{b}Right Amiga + S@{ub}
------------------------------------------
Save the sample you've made with the @{b}Render@{ub} function. You'll get a
file requester wich asks you the name and path and file format.
@endnode

@node Mididu "Menu item 409"
Dump (send) the Midi-data to your sampler - @{b}Right Amiga + M@{ub}
-----------------------------------------------------------
This cool function allows you to send the sample you've made with the
@{b}Render@{ub} function via Midi to a Midi-sampler. So if you have
something like an Akai Sxxxx, you can export the samples of 303tracker
directly to it.

Note: Because of the low transferrate of Midi, be sure the samples are not
      too long in bytes. Otherwise you have to wait for minutes/hours until
      the sample reaches your Midi-sampler. Reasonable lengths are a few
      hundred kilobytes.
@endnode

@node Loadsa "Menu item 411"
Load a Sample into memory - @{b}Right Amiga + L@{ub}
-------------------------------------------
Loads (after a file-requester) a sample, wich can be played with the
@{b}Play Sample@{ub} function. This is useful for 2 things:

1- If you don't know anymore how a certain file sounds.

   Note: If you've loaded one, you'll automaticly jump to the
         @{b}Play Sample@{ub} window.

2- By loading a sample like a rhythm (or anything else of course!) and
   going to the @{b}Play Sample@{ub} window, you can assign this sample
   as the synced sound, wich will be heard if you play the song or pattern.
   This is great if you want to hear how a 303loop sound in combination
   with a rhythm or another sample.
@endnode

@node Playsa "Menu item 412"
Play a Sample from memory - @{b}Right Amiga + P@{ub}
-------------------------------------------
Selecting this item will bring you to the Sample Play window. Here you can
play 2 types of samples:

1-Rendered sample (made with 303tracker's @{b}Render@{ub} function)
2-Loaded sample (external file)

You can assign on of both samples to be the synced sample, wich will be
played along with the 303loop in @{b}Play Pattern@{ub} and @{b}Play Song@{ub}.
@endnode

@node Seteff "Menu item 501"
Set Render Effects - @{b}Alt + E@{ub}
----------------------------
A window will appear where you can set the effects wich will be rendered
along with the 303 sample. You can set 3 types of FX: chorus, delay and
distortion, with each some specific controls. You can also mute each of
them. If you want to mute them all, you can toggle @{b}Apply Effects@{ub}
off in the @{b}Render@{ub} window (found in the menu @{b}Output@{ub}).
@endnode

@node Mikser "Menu item 502"
3 Channel Mixer - @{b}Alt + I@{ub}
-------------------------
A window will appear where you can set the individual volumes of the 3
sources that will be played AND rendered in 303tracker. Again: this mixer
has effect on both the realtime playback and the rendering output.

You can set the level of each source: the Bassline (303), the rhythm, and
an eventual sample which is triggered along with the song.

You can mute each source by activating the mute-button: mute means that it
switches of all output of that source that is muted. In other words it
turns the output level to 0, without pushing the level fader down.
@endnode

@node OscAmp "Menu item 504"
Change 303's Oscillator/Filter/Amplifier Settings - @{b}Alt + V@{ub}
-----------------------------------------------------------
You can change some VCO settings of the TB-303, like Pulse Width Modulation
and others. This gives the possibility to get some non-303 sounds, wich
could add new creative results.

You can change some VCF settings of the TB-303, like what kind of filter
you want. So you're not stuck at only the charachteristic TB-303 sound, but
have a bigger range of the sound-spectrum (something like that!).

You can modify the VCA, to get Arpeggio-like results, wich are initially
impossible on the original TB-303, but IS really cool!
@endnode

@node Shuffl "Menu item 506"
Set Shuffle/Swing Level - @{b}Alt + S@{ub}
---------------------------------
This level sets the amount of shuffle or swing for when playing/rendering a
pattern/song. In other words, the higher the level of shuffle, the more the
odd notes (01, 03, 05, 07 etc) will be played with a short delay, while the
even notes (00, 02, 04, 08 etc) will be played a little earlier than
normal. This gives nice results to get the music sound more hoppier, a word
I invented myself. A graphic shows you the normal linear time/trigger, with
overlayed the time/trigger with shuffle on.
@endnode

@node Playba "Menu item 508"
Set Playback Options - @{b}Alt + P@{ub}
------------------------------
Here you can determine the playback output of 303tracker, to root it to
Paula (Amiga's custom audiochip) or to AHI. In this way it's also possible
to get 16 bit results, wich is a lot cleaner than 8 bit playback.

You can also activate the 'metronome' function, to sync an internal beat
or an external sample file to be played with, while playing a pattern or a
song.
@endnode

@node Audioc "Menu item 509"
Toggle Amiga's Audio Channels On/Off - @{b}Alt + A@{ub}
----------------------------------------------
If you want to run another program wich uses the audio channels, while
303tracker is also running, you have to toggle the audio channels of
303tracker off. This also automaticly happens when you press on the
@{b}Goto Workbench@{ub} button at the top right of 303tracker's screen.
It will also be switched on when you turn back from Workbench to
303tracker.
@endnode

@node Midico "Menu item 511"
Change Midi Settings and Midi Controllers - @{b}Alt + C@{ub}
---------------------------------------------------
A window will pop up, where you can assign some Midi-controllers for the
following parameters: Cutoff, Resonance, Env. Mod, Decay. Possibilities are
that you can use the pitch bender of your synth or a custom Midi-controller
to control 303tracker's parameters.

@{" List of Midi Controller Numbers " link Mclist}
@endnode

@node Midiac "Menu item 512"
Toggle Midi Activity On/Off - @{b}Alt + M@{ub}
-------------------------------------
Reserves or frees the serial.device wich is used to parse the Midi-data
through. This also automaticly happens when you press on the @{b}Goto
Workbench@{ub} button at the top right of 303tracker's screen.
If you want to make use of external Midi controllers, you have to switch
Midi active on.
@endnode

@node Setgri "Menu item 514"
Set Pattern Grid/Highlight - @{b}Right Amiga + G@{ub}
--------------------------------------------
This practical function gives some visual support by placing small marks
every @{b}n@{ub} steps. You can change @{b}n@{ub} (the number of steps) by
entering another value. Examples for @{b}n@{ub} are 4 (every beat), 8 or
16. Default is 4.
@endnode

@node Config "Menu item 516"
Set Configuration - @{b}No keyboard shortcut available@{ub}
-------------------------------------------------
You'll see a window after selecting this item, where you can change the
language settings and the maximum amount of memory, reserved for the
rendered 303 samples.

Also, you can load a configuration or save the new configuration. The
configuration stores the following settings:

- Language
- Pattern Grid/Highlight
- Playback settings
- Metronome settings (wich sample is assigned to play along with the pattern
  or song)
- Midi Controller numbers and settings
@endnode

@node Moreme "Menu item 704"
More Menu - @{b}Alt + T@{ub}
------------------------------
This item reveals/hides an extra row of buttons along with the current
pattern-name replacing the menu-bar. These buttons are made to work
quickly and easy with 303tracker instead of searching in the menus.

Of course, the menu is still available but is not shown until you hold
the right mousebutton, (almost*) just like other, 'normal' Amiga-programs
which use intuition.

(* the mousepointer has to be placed at the above part of the screen when
clicking the right mousebutton to reveal the menu-items. Else, the
'SET RANGE' mode will be activated.)
@endnode

@node Plugin "Menu item 601"
Plug-ins Selection Window
-------------------------
This item brings you to a window where you can select one of the Plug-ins
available in 303tracker.
At the moment (in 303tracker V1.0), there are 2 Plug-ins available:

TB-303 Bassline (Shortcut = @{b}Control + F1@{ub})
-----------------------------------------
This cool feature brings you to a special window with a 'virtual' (I know
it sounds like shit) TB-303 inside. You can program this 303 like you are
programming a real one. This is very nice for people who are not familiar
with 'trackers', but do know how to work with a real TB-303.
For a full guide about programming this 303, click on qpqpqpqpqpqp

Analog Rhythm Machine (Shortcut = @{b}Control + F2@{ub})
-----------------------------------------------
This plug-in gives you the opportunity to create analog bass- snare- hihat-
and clap-sounds, which can be fully programmed from the bottom: VCO, NOISE,
FILTER, VCA. Check out this link for a full description of the Analog
Rhythm Machine: qpqpqpqpqpqpqp

Willy's Wacky Filter Factory (Shortcut = @{b}Control + F3@{ub})
------------------------------------------------------
@endnode

@node Coolto "Menu item 610"
Cool Tools
----------
These are short programs/tools which make editing with 303tracker easier
and enable 303tracker to interact with other programs like Octamed
SoundStudio. Cool Tools are a combination of ARexx Scripts and DOS programs
 bla bla bla
@endnode

@node ARexx1 "Menu item 607"
ARexx-Script Execute Window - @{b}Alt + X@{ub}
-------------------------------------
Brings you a file-requester where you can specify an ARexx script to
execute.
@endnode

@node ARexx2 "Menu item 608"
ARexx script options - no keyboard shortcut available
-----------------------------------------------------
??? Not yet implemented
@endnode

@node Undoac "Menu item 701"
Undo Last Action - @{b}Right Amiga + U@{ub}
----------------------------------
Undoes the last executed action or in other words restores the situation
before your latest change.
@endnode

@node Repeat "Menu item 702"
Repeat Last Action - No keyboard shortcut available
---------------------------------------------------
Repeats the latest action you made.
@endnode

@node Online "Menu item 706"
Goto 303tracker's Online Help Window - @{b}Help@{ub}
-------------------------------------------
Brings you to the mainguide which explains you how to work with 303tracker.

By PRESSING @{b}Help@{ub} however (instead of selecting the menu item),
you'll get some help wich refers to the specific window, menu item, or
button you point at.
@endnode

@node About1 "Menu item 708"
About - @{b}?@{ub}
---------
Gives some general information of 303tracker, along with some greetings.
@endnode

@node Aboutv "Menu item 709"
About Versions
--------------
Gives information about which versions of the routines used in 303tracker
are installed, along with version-numbers of the plug-ins and engines,
loaders and savers.
@endnode

@node Howtoo "Menu item 710"
How to order 303tracker is explained when selecting this menu-item.
@endnode

@node Mclist "Midi Controller Numbers"
Here's a list of default 7 bit Midi Controller Numbers (0-127). As I have a
dutch TB-303 clone Syntecno TeeBee, wich has 5 build in Midi controllers
in the form of potentio-meters, I use them for 303tracker. The controllers
11 to 14 are default defined for cut off, resonance etc. See below.

Deci. Hexa. Description         Deci. Hexa. Description
----- ----- -----------         ----- ----- -----------
 01    01   Modulation Wheel     09    09   Undefined
 02    02   Breath Controller    10    0A   Panorama
 03    03   Undefined            11    0B   Expression Pedal @{b}Cut Off@{ub}
 04    04   Foot Controller      12    0C   Effect Control 1 @{b}Resonance@{ub}
 05    05   Portamento Time      13    0D   Effect Control 2 @{b}Env.Mod.@{ub}
 06    06   Data Entry Slider    14    0E   Undefined        @{b}Decay@{ub}
 07    07   Main Volume          15    0F   Undefined
 08    08   Balance              16    10   General use
@endnode

@node Copyco "Column option 1"
Copy Column - @{b}Shift + F4@{ub}
------------------------
Copies a part or the whole selected column into buffer. Use @{b}Paste Column@{ub}
to copy the contents of this buffer into another column.
You can select a column by clicking on the head of it, or using the @{b}TAB@{ub}
key.

Possibility 2: You can also copy,paste and clear the WHOLE column at once.

@{b}Shift@{ub} + @{b}F3@{ub}      - Cut selected column to buffer
@{b}Shift@{ub} + @{b}F4@{ub}      - Copy selected column to buffer
@{b}Shift@{ub} + @{b}F5@{ub}      - Paste buffer to selected column
@endnode

@node Pastec "Column option 2"
Paste Column - @{b}Shift + F5@{ub}
-------------------------
Copies the contents of the buffer into the selected column.
You can select a column by clicking on the head of it, or using the @{b}TAB@{ub}
key.

Possibility 2: You can also copy,paste and clear the WHOLE column at once.

@{b}Shift@{ub} + @{b}F3@{ub}      - Cut selected column to buffer
@{b}Shift@{ub} + @{b}F4@{ub}      - Copy selected column to buffer
@{b}Shift@{ub} + @{b}F5@{ub}      - Paste buffer to selected column
@endnode

@node Clearc "Column option 3"
Cut Column - @{b}Shift + F3@{ub}
-----------------------
Erases (a part of) the selected column after storing it into a buffer.

You can select a column by clicking on the head of it, or using the @{b}TAB@{ub}
key.

Possibility 2: You can also copy,paste and clear the WHOLE column at once.

@{b}Shift@{ub} + @{b}F3@{ub}      - Cut selected column to buffer
@{b}Shift@{ub} + @{b}F4@{ub}      - Copy selected column to buffer
@{b}Shift@{ub} + @{b}F5@{ub}      - Paste buffer to selected column
@endnode

@node Swapco "Column option 4"
Swap Selected Column With... - @{b}No keyboard shortcut available@{ub}
-------------------------------------------------------------
With this function you can swap the contents of the selected column with
